SENATE RESOLUTION NO. 151
BY SENATOR FOIL
A RESOLUTION
To express the sincere and heartfelt condolences of the Senate of the Legislature of
Louisiana upon the passing of Edith Kay Kirkpatrick.
WHEREAS, the Baton Rouge community and the State of Louisiana suffered a
profound loss with the passing of Edith Kay Kirkpatrick on Sunday, May 10, 2026; and
WHEREAS, Edith Kay Kirkpatrick, affectionately known as "Kay", was born in
Jennings, Louisiana, on July 14, 1946, to her parents, Claude and Edith Kirkpatrick; and
WHEREAS, from a young age, Kay displayed remarkable musical talent and, at just
twelve years old, earned recognition as a childhood prodigy through her performance of a
piano solo with the New Orleans Philharmonic Orchestra; and
WHEREAS, at the age of thirteen, she moved with her family to Baton Rouge, where
she attended Lee High School and was recognized for her academic excellence, character,
and leadership, serving as student body vice president and being voted "Most Likely to
Succeed"; and
WHEREAS, in 1963, Kay attended Louisiana Girls State and returned in 1964 as a
counselor, after which she served as a volunteer and frequent speaker at Girls State
conventions; and
WHEREAS, while attending Louisiana State University, she was an active member
of Chi Omega sorority serving as an officer and participating in Angel Flight, ultimately
rising to the rank of national commander; and
WHEREAS, Kay graduated with her first degree from Louisiana State University in
1968, the same year her brother completed LSU Law School, and desired to follow him into
the legal profession; and
WHEREAS, after graduating with a master's degree and a PhD in Speech and
Psycholinguistics, she later earned a law degree from LSU and was admitted to the bar in
1977; and
