WHEREAS, her early legal career with East Baton Rouge Parish District Attorney
Ossie Brown included distinguishing herself as the "go-to" person for matters before the
state appellate courts and the Louisiana Supreme Court on behalf of the District Attorney;
and
WHEREAS, in 1988, Governor Buddy Roemer appointed Kay as Assistant Executive
Counsel to the Governor, where her responsibilities expanded beyond criminal law to
include environmental, fiscal, educational, and other policy matters including key decisions
affecting the state and its citizens; and
WHEREAS, in 1992, Attorney General Richard Ieyoub appointed her as Deputy
Attorney General in charge of the Civil Division, where she handled a majority of the
office's work and participated in negotiations with the United States Department of Justice
regarding challenges to the state's higher education system; and
WHEREAS, Kay concluded her distinguished public service career as General
Counsel for the University of Louisiana System; and
WHEREAS, she generously supported LSU Law School by establishing the E. Kay
Kirkpatrick Endowed Superior Graduate Scholarship in Public Law to inspire future
attorneys pursuing careers in government and public law; and
WHEREAS, Kay leaves to cherish her memory her brother, Charles Kris Kirkpatrick,
and his wife, Jane; her sister-in-law, Sandra Futrell Kirkpatrick; and numerous beloved
nieces, nephews, extended family members, and close friends, all of whom were blessed to
know her.
THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED, that the Senate of the Legislature of Louisiana
extends its deepest sympathy and heartfelt condolences to the family and loved ones of Edith
Kay Kirkpatrick.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that a copy of this Resolution be transmitted to the
family of Edith Kay Kirkpatrick.
PRESIDENT OF THE SENATE
